export const QUESTIONS = {"office_professional":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently handling your firm's bookkeeping and financial reporting — do you have a dedicated controller, an outside CPA, or is it managed internally?","goodResponse":"That setup gives me a sense of how your financial function is staffed right now. I want to understand what your monthly close and reporting timeline looks like.","badResponse":"We work with professional services firms on their financial function.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are your partners getting timely, accurate financial reports each month — or is there often a lag between the end of the month and when the numbers are actually ready to review?","goodResponse":"That reporting lag is where most firms lose their financial visibility. Decisions get made on stale data, and the monthly close becomes a scramble instead of a routine.","badResponse":"We accelerate the close and get you current numbers faster.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're making partner compensation, hiring, or investment decisions based on financial reports that are 45 or 60 days old — and the business has shifted significantly in that window — what decisions might you be making incorrectly?","goodResponse":"Stale data means delayed reactions. In a firm where partners are making significant decisions monthly, that lag has a compounding cost.","badResponse":"Old data leads to bad decisions. We get you current.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had accurate, reviewed financial statements ready by the fifth business day each month — and a dashboard showing utilization, realization, and cash position in real time — how would that change how you manage the firm?","goodResponse":"That visibility is what transforms financial management from reactive to strategic. Let me walk you through what our outsourced CFO and accounting service delivers.","badResponse":"We provide that reporting cadence. Let's talk scope.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do your partners have a clear view of which practice areas and client relationships are most profitable — or does everything get rolled up into firm-wide numbers that make it hard to see the real picture?","goodResponse":"Practice-level profitability is one of the most powerful tools for firm management, and most firms that don't have it are making resource allocation decisions blind.","badResponse":"We build practice-level profitability reporting for professional firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a situation where a practice group or a major client relationship looked profitable on the surface but, when you dug into the hours and overhead allocation, turned out to be breaking even or worse?","goodResponse":"That discovery is often a turning point for firms. What did you do with that information, and how did it change how you looked at that relationship or group?","badResponse":"Hidden unprofitability is a common problem. We surface it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're actively growing a practice group that looks busy but is actually dragging overall firm profitability — and you're allocating partner time and support staff to it — what does that misallocation cost you annually?","goodResponse":"The opportunity cost of growing the wrong thing is often the biggest financial drag in professional firms. The partners with the clearest picture make better choices.","badResponse":"Growing unprofitable practices is expensive. We identify them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a clear profitability breakdown by client, matter type, and practice group — updated monthly — how would that change your partner conversations about where to invest and what to sunset?","goodResponse":"That's the data that makes difficult partner conversations productive instead of political. Let me show you what that reporting framework looks like.","badResponse":"We build that reporting. It changes firm strategy fast.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you handling tax planning for the firm's partners — is that handled through the same accountant who does the firm's returns, or do partners manage their personal tax situation separately?","goodResponse":"Integrated firm and partner tax planning is where a lot of value gets left behind. Understanding the current structure helps me see where the planning gaps might be.","badResponse":"We handle integrated firm and partner tax planning for professional firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are the partners at your firm proactively planning their quarterly estimated taxes, retirement contributions, and entity structure — or is tax strategy mostly a year-end conversation after the damage is done?","goodResponse":"Year-end planning is too late for most of the meaningful moves. What does your current dialogue with your CPA look like throughout the year?","badResponse":"Proactive tax planning saves significantly versus reactive.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If the partners aren't maximizing retirement contributions, reviewing entity structure annually, or leveraging the tax benefits available to high-income professionals — what are they leaving on the table each year, and how does that compound over a career?","goodResponse":"The compounding effect of consistent proactive planning versus reactive year-end scrambling is often six figures over a decade. That's not a theoretical number — we can run it.","badResponse":"Missed planning is real money. We find those opportunities.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your firm had a proactive tax planning relationship — quarterly check-ins, retirement strategy, entity review, and projected liability updates — what would that look like in annual tax savings for a typical partner at your income level?","goodResponse":"That's the conversation that pays for itself very quickly. Let me put together a planning estimate for a partner profile like yours.","badResponse":"We do that planning. Let's model what it looks like for you.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"tech_company":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"At your current stage, are you managing your books internally, through a part-time bookkeeper, or do you have a formal accounting and finance function in place?","goodResponse":"The accounting maturity of a company usually lags its operational growth. Understanding where you are right now helps me see what's likely coming up as you scale.","badResponse":"We scale financial functions for growing tech companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"As you're growing — adding headcount, new revenue streams, maybe some international exposure — are you confident your accounting and financial reporting can keep up, or is it starting to feel like it's held together with duct tape?","goodResponse":"That 'duct tape' feeling is very common at the Series A / B stage. What does your current monthly close process look like, and how long does it take?","badResponse":"We build scalable finance functions for growth-stage companies.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your financial reporting isn't investor-grade when you go into your next funding round — and a data room review reveals inconsistencies or delays — how does that affect your negotiating position and your valuation?","goodResponse":"Investors price in operational risk, and messy books signal operational immaturity. Clean financials aren't just a compliance requirement — they're a valuation lever.","badResponse":"Messy books hurt valuation. We get you investor-grade.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a fractional CFO and an accounting team that could get you to investor-grade reporting within 60 days — and stay alongside you through the next round — what would that confidence be worth going into due diligence?","goodResponse":"That readiness is worth significantly more than the cost in deal terms alone. Let me walk you through how our fractional CFO engagement works for companies at your stage.","badResponse":"We provide that. Let's scope the engagement.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently tracking and reporting on SaaS-specific metrics — ARR, churn, LTV, CAC payback — and are those coming out of your accounting system or from separate spreadsheets?","goodResponse":"SaaS metrics living in spreadsheets is a common early-stage reality. It tells me there's probably some reconciliation headache happening between what finance sees and what the business sees.","badResponse":"We build SaaS financial reporting with proper metric visibility.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had a board meeting where the ARR number from finance didn't match what your head of sales thought the number was — and you spent part of the meeting resolving the discrepancy instead of discussing strategy?","goodResponse":"That reconciliation fight in the boardroom is embarrassing and expensive. What's causing the discrepancy — is it timing, definition, or just data hygiene?","badResponse":"We align financial and operational metrics so that never happens.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your board or investors have lost confidence in the accuracy of the numbers coming out of your finance team — even temporarily — what does that do to the working relationship and to their confidence in the team running the company?","goodResponse":"Investor confidence in financial reporting is foundational. Once it's shaken, it takes a long time to rebuild. Clean, reconciled numbers are the baseline for every other conversation.","badResponse":"Bad data costs credibility. We fix the underlying systems.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If finance, sales, and your board were all looking at the same real-time ARR, churn, and cohort data — from one source of truth — how would that change how your board meetings run?","goodResponse":"When everyone trusts the numbers, the conversation moves to strategy instead of arithmetic. That's where companies make better decisions. Let me show you how we build that.","badResponse":"We build that single source of truth. Let's talk stack.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you doing any financial modeling or scenario planning — runway, headcount projections, revenue forecasting — or is long-range planning mostly done at budget time and then forgotten?","goodResponse":"Budget-and-forget planning is common, but it means you're only seeing the road ahead once a year. In a growth environment, that's often not enough visibility.","badResponse":"We build dynamic financial models for growth-stage companies.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a situation where you hired ahead of revenue — or delayed a key hire because of cash uncertainty — and only realized the miscalculation when you were already in it?","goodResponse":"Headcount timing is one of the most consequential and hardest-to-undo financial decisions a growth company makes. What does your current visibility into 6 to 12 month runway look like?","badResponse":"We build models that remove that hiring uncertainty.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you miss a key hire timing by a quarter because you didn't have clear runway visibility — and a competitor who did have that visibility made the move — what does that talent and speed-to-market gap cost you?","goodResponse":"Hiring velocity is a competitive weapon in tech. The companies with clear financial models make faster and better decisions. That's not a small advantage at your stage.","badResponse":"Hiring delays have competitive costs. Better models fix that.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a live financial model that showed three scenarios — base, upside, downside — and updated automatically with your actual numbers each month, how would that change the confidence with which you make hiring and investment decisions?","goodResponse":"That's the planning environment that top-performing boards expect. Let me show you what our financial modeling and fractional CFO service delivers.","badResponse":"We build those models. Let's talk about your planning horizon.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"healthcare":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"Who currently handles your practice's accounting and financial reporting — do you have an in-house office manager doing it, an outside bookkeeper, or a CPA firm?","goodResponse":"Healthcare accounting has some specific complexity — insurance billing reconciliation, provider comp modeling, Medicare compliance — that general bookkeepers often miss. Let me understand the current setup.","badResponse":"We specialize in healthcare practice accounting and finance.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Do you have clean visibility into your collections rate, your days in accounts receivable, and where your biggest insurance payer lag is — or are those numbers hard to pin down?","goodResponse":"AR management is where most practices bleed money silently. If those numbers aren't clear, there's usually more in the pipeline than you realize — and more slipping through.","badResponse":"We give practices clear AR visibility and faster collections.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your days-in-AR is running high because of payer delays, coding issues, or claims that aren't being followed up on — what does that uncollected revenue represent on an annualized basis for a practice your size?","goodResponse":"For most practices, improving AR management by even a few days translates to tens of thousands in additional cash flow annually. It's one of the highest-leverage financial levers available.","badResponse":"AR inefficiency costs real money. We recover it for you.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a financial team that specialized in healthcare practice accounting — managing your AR, reconciling payer remittances, and giving you a monthly dashboard of your key financial health metrics — what would that free you up to focus on?","goodResponse":"That's usually the answer providers give when they're asked what success looks like — spending more time practicing and less time chasing money. Let me walk you through our healthcare accounting service.","badResponse":"We specialize in exactly that. Let's talk about your practice.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are provider compensation and productivity tracked at your practice — is that built into your billing software, tracked manually, or does someone build a spreadsheet each month?","goodResponse":"Provider comp modeling is one of the most complex and sensitive financial tasks in a practice. Understanding how it's handled tells me a lot about the financial operations maturity.","badResponse":"We handle provider comp modeling for practices of all sizes.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had providers question their comp calculation — or had disputes about productivity metrics — because the numbers came from different sources and didn't reconcile cleanly?","goodResponse":"Provider comp disputes are morale-killers and retention risks. What does the reconciliation process look like when a provider questions the numbers?","badResponse":"We eliminate comp calculation disputes with clean, reconciled data.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a high-producing provider loses confidence in the fairness or accuracy of their comp calculation — and starts looking at other opportunities — what does replacing that provider cost the practice in recruitment, credentialing, and lost production?","goodResponse":"Provider replacement cost is often underestimated. It's not just the search — it's the ramp-up time, the credentialing lag, and the patients who follow the departing provider. Clean comp builds trust.","badResponse":"Provider attrition is expensive. Compensation clarity reduces it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If every provider received a clear, reconciled monthly comp statement — sourced from the same billing data as the practice's own P&L — how would that change the trust level in your provider group?","goodResponse":"Transparent, consistent comp reporting is one of the best retention tools a practice administrator has. Let me show you what that reporting looks like.","badResponse":"We build that reporting. It's a meaningful retention tool.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you actively planning for the long-term financial structure of the practice — partnership buyouts, succession, or potential sale — or is that something that's on the horizon but hasn't been formally addressed yet?","goodResponse":"Practice succession planning is one of the most underplanned financial areas for healthcare providers. Understanding where you are in that thinking helps me see where the gaps might be.","badResponse":"We help practices plan for ownership transitions and succession.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"If you were to bring in a new partner or sell the practice in the next five to ten years, do you have a current, defensible valuation — and is your financial documentation clean enough to support a transaction?","goodResponse":"Most practices that end up in a transaction situation wish they'd started the financial cleanup three to five years earlier. What does your current practice valuation picture look like?","badResponse":"We prepare practices for transactions and ownership transitions.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a group or private equity buyer comes to you with an interest in acquiring the practice — and your books aren't clean, your AR isn't current, and your profitability metrics are unclear — how does that affect the price you're able to negotiate?","goodResponse":"Financial opacity is a negotiating disadvantage in every transaction. Buyers discount for uncertainty, and that discount comes directly out of your exit number.","badResponse":"Messy books reduce your exit value. We fix that proactively.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your practice had clean financials, a current valuation, and a documented financial narrative ready to go — what would that mean for your negotiating confidence in any future transaction or partnership discussion?","goodResponse":"That preparation is worth real money at the table. Let me walk you through our practice financial advisory service and what the exit readiness process looks like.","badResponse":"We do that advisory work. Let's talk about your timeline.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"retail_food":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently handling your bookkeeping and monthly financial reports — is that you personally, a part-time bookkeeper, or do you have a CPA who touches it regularly?","goodResponse":"Owner-managed books are common in food and retail, but they usually create a situation where the numbers are months behind and tax planning is reactive. Let me understand the current setup.","badResponse":"We handle bookkeeping and financial reporting for retail and food businesses.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Do you know what your actual food cost or inventory cost as a percentage of revenue looks like right now — and is that tracked weekly or is it more of a quarterly number?","goodResponse":"Cost of goods visibility is the most important financial lever in food and retail. If that number is only quarterly, there's usually a lot of margin leakage happening in the gaps.","badResponse":"We track cost percentages weekly so you can see the leaks.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your food cost is running two or three points above where it should be — because of waste, portioning, or theft — and you don't find out until the quarterly review, how much profit has already left the building?","goodResponse":"Two or three margin points on a busy location can be five figures a year. The sooner you see it, the faster you can fix it. Weekly visibility changes the response time completely.","badResponse":"Margin leakage is real money. We catch it faster.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a weekly financial snapshot showing your cost percentages, gross margin, and cash position — updated automatically from your POS and accounting system — what decisions would you make differently?","goodResponse":"That visibility changes how owners manage labor, purchasing, and menu pricing. Let me show you what that dashboard looks like for a business like yours.","badResponse":"We build that dashboard. Let's get your systems connected.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Are you on top of your quarterly estimated tax payments, or is your tax situation mostly handled at year-end and you're sometimes surprised by what you owe?","goodResponse":"Year-end surprises are one of the most stressful financial experiences for small business owners. Let me understand your current relationship with your CPA and how proactive the planning is.","badResponse":"We do proactive tax planning for small business owners.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever gotten to April and owed significantly more than you expected — or paid a penalty for underpayment — because the quarterly estimates weren't calibrated to your actual income?","goodResponse":"Underpayment penalties are the most preventable tax cost there is. What does your current quarterly planning conversation with your CPA look like?","badResponse":"We eliminate underpayment surprises with proper quarterly planning.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're consistently underpaying estimates and getting hit with penalties — and you're also not maximizing the deductions available to a business your structure — what's the combined tax inefficiency costing you each year?","goodResponse":"Most small business owners are overpaying taxes by some amount every year through missed deductions and poor quarterly calibration. That's money that could stay in the business.","badResponse":"Missed deductions and penalties add up. We find and prevent them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your CPA was proactively managing your quarterly estimates, reviewing your deduction strategy mid-year, and you went into tax season knowing your number within a small range — how much less stressful would your financial life be?","goodResponse":"That predictability is worth a lot. Let me walk you through what a proactive small business tax planning relationship looks like.","badResponse":"We provide that planning relationship. Let's talk about your structure.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you have multiple locations or are thinking about expanding, how are you currently evaluating whether a new location or investment makes financial sense — do you have a model for that, or is it more gut and opportunity?","goodResponse":"Expansion decisions made without a solid financial model are where a lot of great operators get into trouble. Let me understand how you've approached that analysis historically.","badResponse":"We build expansion models for food and retail operators.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever committed to a new location or a significant investment and found that the actual financial performance was very different from what you anticipated — in a way that stressed your cash flow?","goodResponse":"That gap between projected and actual is almost always a modeling problem, not an execution problem. What did the analysis look like before you went in?","badResponse":"We build models that close that gap between projected and actual.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If an underperforming second location is drawing cash from your first location to survive — instead of becoming self-sustaining as planned — how does that constrain your ability to make other investments or build reserves?","goodResponse":"Cash drag from a struggling location can freeze the whole business. The model that prevents it has to be built before the lease is signed, not after.","badResponse":"Cash drag is hard to recover from. Better modeling prevents it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a financial model that scenario-tested a new location before you committed — break-even timeline, cash requirements, contribution to your overall portfolio — how much more confident would you feel pulling the trigger on the right opportunities?","goodResponse":"That confidence is the difference between smart growth and risky growth. Let me walk you through how we build those expansion models for operators like you.","badResponse":"We build those models. Let's run one on your next opportunity.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"trades_contractor":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently tracking job costs — labor, materials, subcontractors — and are those matched against the original estimate to see if you came in on budget?","goodResponse":"Job cost tracking is the financial heartbeat of a contracting business. Most contractors either don't do it at all or do it after the fact. What does your current process look like?","badResponse":"We build job cost accounting systems for contractors.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Do you know which types of jobs you're most profitable on — and which ones you're consistently underpricing or underestimating — or does it all kind of average out at the end of the year?","goodResponse":"Averaging out means you're probably subsidizing your least profitable job types with your most profitable ones. Identifying that split changes how you price and what you bid.","badResponse":"Job profitability analysis tells you where to focus. We build it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're consistently underpricing a certain job category — commercial versus residential, for example — and you've been winning a lot of those jobs, what does that margin gap add up to over a year of work?","goodResponse":"It's one of the most expensive realizations for a contractor — staying busy but not actually growing. The fix starts with knowing exactly where the margin is going.","badResponse":"Underpriced jobs mean real losses at scale. We find them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you knew after every job whether you came in over or under budget — and could see patterns in where you were winning or losing margin — how would that change your estimating and bidding strategy?","goodResponse":"That feedback loop is what separates growing contractors from ones that plateau. Let me show you what job cost accounting looks like when it's built into your workflow.","badResponse":"We build that feedback loop. Let's talk about your accounting setup.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you managing cash flow across projects — are you collecting deposits upfront, billing milestone draws, and keeping a cushion — or does cash get tight between jobs sometimes?","goodResponse":"Cash flow management in contracting is notoriously difficult because of the gap between when you pay your subs and materials and when you get paid by the GC or owner. Let me understand the current pattern.","badResponse":"We help contractors build cash flow structures that smooth the gaps.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever had to delay payroll, pass on a good job opportunity, or carry credit card debt because cash was tight between receivables coming in?","goodResponse":"Those cash crunches are symptoms of a receivables timing problem, and they have a way of compounding if not managed proactively. What does your typical receivables aging look like?","badResponse":"Cash crunches are solvable with better financial structure. We build it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a cash crunch forces you to pass on a profitable job because you can't fund the materials — or to delay a key hire because you're not sure what's coming in — what does that cost you in revenue and growth?","goodResponse":"Opportunity cost from cash crunches is one of the hardest things to measure but one of the most real constraints on contractor growth. The fix is almost always in the billing and receivables process.","badResponse":"Missed opportunities have real costs. We fix the cash timing.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your billing was structured to maximize early cash collection — deposits, milestones, retainage management — and you had a 13-week cash flow forecast updated weekly, how differently would you approach growth decisions?","goodResponse":"Contractors with cash flow visibility make bolder and better growth moves. That's the operating environment we help you build. Let me walk you through our contractor financial management service.","badResponse":"We build that visibility. Let's talk about your project mix.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently handling your business taxes — is it a local CPA at year-end, or do you have someone engaged throughout the year who understands the construction-specific deductions available to you?","goodResponse":"Construction has some very specific tax treatment — bonus depreciation on equipment, Section 179, percentage-of-completion versus completed contract — that generalist CPAs often don't optimize for.","badResponse":"We specialize in contractor and construction tax optimization.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are you depreciating your equipment and vehicles in a way that maximizes your current-year deductions — or are those assets being depreciated on a straight-line schedule that leaves money on the table each year?","goodResponse":"Most contractors aren't aware of how aggressive the depreciation options are under current tax law. Section 179 and bonus depreciation can be significant for a business with your equipment base.","badResponse":"Equipment depreciation is a major tax lever for contractors. We maximize it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you bought $200,000 in equipment last year and it's being depreciated over seven years instead of written off immediately under bonus depreciation — what's the tax deferral you gave up, and what could that cash have done in the business?","goodResponse":"That's usually a five-figure difference in year-one tax liability. The deferred benefit eventually comes, but having that cash now is worth significantly more for a growing business.","badResponse":"Deferred deductions cost cash now. We accelerate them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a CPA who proactively reviewed your equipment purchases, entity structure, and project accounting throughout the year to maximize deductions — what would that look like in annual tax savings at your revenue level?","goodResponse":"For a contractor your size, proactive planning typically saves meaningfully more than it costs. Let me put some preliminary numbers around what that looks like for your situation.","badResponse":"We do contractor tax planning. Let's model what it means for you.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"auto_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How is your dealership or shop's accounting handled right now — do you have an in-house controller, a bookkeeper, or are you working with an outside firm?","goodResponse":"Automotive accounting has some specific complexity — flooring interest, pack, dealer trades, warranty accounting — that a general bookkeeper often misses. Let me understand the current setup.","badResponse":"We specialize in automotive dealership and shop accounting.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Do you have a clear picture of your front-end gross versus back-end gross by deal — and how those numbers are trending against your targets month over month?","goodResponse":"A lot of dealers have the data in their DMS but don't have the reporting to surface the story quickly. What does your monthly financial review look like?","badResponse":"We build reporting that surfaces those gross margin trends clearly.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your back-end gross is declining because F&I penetration rates are slipping — and you don't catch that until the monthly composite — how many deals have already gone through with underperforming finance penetration?","goodResponse":"F&I is often where the real profitability lives, and catching a penetration decline a month late is expensive. What's your current process for catching those trends in real time?","badResponse":"Late reporting means late correction. We build faster visibility.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a weekly financial dashboard showing front-end gross, back-end gross, F&I penetration, and service absorption by department — live and without waiting for the monthly close — how would that change how you manage the store?","goodResponse":"That's the financial visibility that top-performing dealers are running on. Let me walk you through what our automotive accounting and reporting solution looks like.","badResponse":"We build that dashboard. Let's connect it to your DMS.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently managing your floor plan financing — do you have good visibility into what's aged, what's accruing interest, and what your flooring cost per vehicle is running?","goodResponse":"Floor plan management is one of the biggest variable costs at a dealership, and it's one of the most undermanaged. What does your current aged inventory reporting look like?","badResponse":"We build floor plan cost management reports for dealers.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had vehicles age past 60 or 90 days on the floor plan because the reporting wasn't surfacing them clearly — and by the time you discounted them out, the margin was mostly eaten by flooring costs?","goodResponse":"Aged inventory is a silent profit killer. The flooring interest compounds while the vehicle's market value usually deteriorates simultaneously — a double margin squeeze. How often does that pattern play out?","badResponse":"We surface aged inventory before flooring cost destroys the margin.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you have five or six vehicles aging past 75 days every month — paying flooring interest daily — what does that add up to annually in flooring cost on units that are eventually sold at a loss?","goodResponse":"When you run that math, the number is usually significant enough that a proper aged inventory reporting system pays for itself in the first quarter.","badResponse":"Flooring cost on aged units is a real drag. We help you see and fix it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had an automated aged inventory report that flagged every vehicle approaching 45 days, with the current flooring cost and market value comparison — how would that change your pricing and sourcing decisions?","goodResponse":"Dealers with that visibility make better stocking and pricing moves faster. Let me show you what that reporting module looks like inside our automotive accounting suite.","badResponse":"We build that. It pays for itself fast. Let's talk.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are service department financials tracked separately from the new and used vehicle operations — do you have clean departmental P&Ls, or does everything roll up together?","goodResponse":"Departmental P&Ls are essential for a dealership to understand its real profitability. Without them, a strong fixed ops can mask a struggling variable ops, or vice versa.","badResponse":"We build departmental P&L reporting for automotive operations.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Do you know what your service department's absorption rate is right now — the percentage of fixed costs that fixed ops covers — and is it where you need it to be to protect profitability in a slow sales month?","goodResponse":"Most dealers cite absorption rate as a key metric but don't have real-time visibility into it. What does your current fixed ops reporting cadence look like?","badResponse":"Absorption rate visibility helps you manage risk in the business cycle.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If your service absorption rate drops below 100% during a slow vehicle sales period and you don't have that visibility until the month is over — how exposed is the dealership's bottom line when both departments underperform simultaneously?","goodResponse":"That double squeeze is where dealerships get into real financial trouble. The ones with real-time departmental visibility can make decisions mid-month instead of post-mortem.","badResponse":"Double-department underperformance is serious. Better reporting prevents it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had weekly departmental P&Ls — with absorption rate, effective labor rate, and CP versus warranty mix all visible in one report — how would that change your management conversations with your fixed ops director?","goodResponse":"That's the operating data that drives better decisions. Let me walk you through our dealership accounting and reporting solution.","badResponse":"We build that reporting. Let's connect it to your DMS.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"financial_services":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How is the financial firm's own accounting handled — internally by an ops person, or through an outside CPA who specializes in financial services entities?","goodResponse":"Financial services entities have some unique accounting complexity — revenue recognition on AUM fees, deferred compensation, principal transactions — that a generalist CPA often doesn't navigate optimally.","badResponse":"We specialize in accounting for financial services firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are the principals at your firm doing proactive personal and entity-level tax planning — or is that primarily a year-end exercise because everyone's focused on client planning instead of their own?","goodResponse":"Financial professionals often have the least well-managed personal financial planning of anyone — because they spend all day doing it for clients and have no energy left for themselves.","badResponse":"We do the financial planning for the advisors themselves.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If the principals of a firm are missing deferred compensation strategies, retirement plan optimization, or entity restructuring opportunities every year — what does that look like in after-tax wealth accumulation over a 10-year career?","goodResponse":"The number is usually very meaningful for high-income professionals. And the irony of financial professionals being underserved on their own planning is not lost on anyone when they finally see it.","badResponse":"Missed personal planning has a real compounding cost. We quantify it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a CPA firm that handled both the firm's entity accounting and proactive personal planning for each principal — with coordinated strategies — what would that simplicity and optimization look like in your annual tax picture?","goodResponse":"Coordinated entity and personal planning is where the biggest savings usually live. Let me show you what that engagement looks like for a firm like yours.","badResponse":"We do that coordinated planning. Let's talk structure.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"Do you use a budgeting and forecasting process for the firm — projecting revenue, headcount costs, and operating expenses — or is the financial planning informal?","goodResponse":"Given that your revenue is largely AUM-based, a formal model that scenarios out market fluctuations on revenue is especially important. What does planning look like today?","badResponse":"We build financial models for advisory and brokerage firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"In a year when markets pull back significantly and AUM fees compress, do you have visibility into what that means for your fixed cost coverage — and what you'd need to cut or adjust to maintain profitability?","goodResponse":"Most advisory firms don't scenario-plan for a 20 or 30% AUM decline until it's already happening. What did 2022 look like for the firm's own financials?","badResponse":"Scenario planning protects the firm through market cycles.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a prolonged market downturn compressed your revenue by 25% while your fixed costs — rent, salaries, technology — stayed constant, and you hadn't pre-planned for that scenario, how long does the firm's reserve runway last?","goodResponse":"Most principals haven't run that number explicitly. When they do, it either confirms they're in good shape or it's a wake-up call. Either way, knowing is better.","badResponse":"Reserve runway visibility is critical for firm stability. We model it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a financial model for the firm that updated monthly with actuals and showed three market scenarios — what would that do for how you think about compensation, hiring, and capital reserves?","goodResponse":"That's the operating intelligence that keeps firms stable through volatility. Let me walk you through what our financial services firm advisory practice looks like.","badResponse":"We build that model. Let's connect it to your revenue data.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"If you're thinking about bringing on a junior partner or selling equity in the firm, do you have a current, documented valuation of the entity — and a clear framework for how that equity is priced?","goodResponse":"Firm valuation is one of the most sensitive and consequential conversations in an advisory practice. Understanding where the documentation stands helps me see the preparation level.","badResponse":"We do financial services firm valuation and succession planning.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you had a conversation with a junior advisor or a potential partner where you needed to explain the firm's value — and found it difficult to articulate a defensible number because the formal valuation work hadn't been done?","goodResponse":"That conversation being difficult is a signal that the work hasn't been documented. What does the basis for the firm's value look like in your current thinking?","badResponse":"We build valuations that make those conversations clear and defensible.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you're negotiating an internal equity sale with a junior partner without a formal valuation — and they later feel the price wasn't fair — what does that do to the partnership relationship and to retaining the person you were trying to incentivize?","goodResponse":"Equity disputes with key people are existential for advisory firms. A documented, methodology-backed valuation protects both parties and makes the conversation professional.","badResponse":"Undocumented equity creates disputes. We formalize the valuation.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had a current, defensible valuation of the firm — with a documented methodology and an updated schedule each year — how much more confidently could you have succession and partnership conversations?","goodResponse":"That documentation is a management and planning tool, not just a transaction tool. Let me walk you through our advisory firm valuation and succession planning service.","badResponse":"We do that work. Let's talk about the timeline.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]],"real_estate":[[{"phase":"situation","question":"How are you currently handling the accounting across your properties or transactions — do you have a property management accounting system, or is it a mix of QuickBooks and spreadsheets?","goodResponse":"Real estate accounting has some specific requirements — depreciation schedules, entity structuring, cost segregation — that general bookkeeping tools often don't handle well. Let me understand the setup.","badResponse":"We do accounting and tax planning for real estate investors and firms.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Are you confident that your depreciation is being calculated correctly and that you're capturing all the deductions available to you — including cost segregation on any commercial or multi-family assets?","goodResponse":"Cost segregation is one of the most underutilized tax strategies in real estate, and it's almost never being done by default in a standard accounting setup.","badResponse":"Cost segregation is a major tax lever we optimize for real estate owners.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you acquired a commercial property in the last five years and haven't done a cost segregation study — the potential accelerated depreciation you've missed could represent a significant tax deferral. How does that factor into your current cash position and tax strategy?","goodResponse":"On a commercial property, a cost segregation study often generates immediate-year deductions that dwarf the cost of the study many times over. That's a real opportunity cost to quantify.","badResponse":"Missed cost segregation is a real dollar amount. We recover it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If we reviewed your current portfolio for cost segregation opportunities and optimized your entity structure for real estate tax purposes — what would the projected tax savings look like in year one?","goodResponse":"That projected number usually makes the engagement decision straightforward. Let me put together a preliminary review of your property portfolio.","badResponse":"We do that analysis. Let's look at your portfolio.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"How is your entity structure set up for holding real estate — are properties in individual LLCs, a series LLC, a trust, or is everything still in your personal name?","goodResponse":"Entity structure for real estate has significant liability and tax implications that change as the portfolio grows. Understanding the current structure helps me identify where the risks and opportunities are.","badResponse":"We advise on entity structure for real estate investors and developers.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"If a tenant at one of your properties filed a significant liability claim — a slip-and-fall or a habitability dispute — are the assets in your other properties protected from that judgment?","goodResponse":"Asset protection is the primary reason to structure carefully, and most investors don't think about it until there's a claim. What does your current liability exposure look like across the portfolio?","badResponse":"Improper structure leaves assets exposed. We protect them.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If a judgment attached to a property that's cross-collateralized or held in the same entity as your other assets — and it was large enough to force a sale — what does that mean for your overall portfolio and your long-term wealth plan?","goodResponse":"One event liquidating a portfolio that took years to build is the nightmare scenario. The right entity structure costs very little to build and can prevent exactly that outcome.","badResponse":"Cross-entity liability is a serious risk. We structure away from it.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If your portfolio was structured so that each property's liability was ring-fenced from the others — and the entity setup was also optimized for tax efficiency — how much more confident would you feel adding to the portfolio?","goodResponse":"That structural confidence is what enables aggressive portfolio growth. Let me walk you through what the right real estate entity framework looks like for a portfolio your size.","badResponse":"We build that structure. Let's map your current portfolio.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}],[{"phase":"situation","question":"When you're evaluating a new acquisition or development deal, what does your financial underwriting process look like — do you have a model, or is the analysis more informal?","goodResponse":"Deal underwriting quality is the single biggest determinant of long-term portfolio performance. Understanding how rigorous the current process is tells me where the risk might be sitting.","badResponse":"We build underwriting models and do deal analysis for real estate investors.","rapportOnGood":1,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"situation_questions","framework":"SPIN – Situation"},{"phase":"problem","question":"Have you ever closed on a deal where the actual NOI, cap rate, or cash-on-cash return was significantly worse than the broker's pro forma suggested — because the underwriting assumptions were too optimistic?","goodResponse":"Broker pro formas are marketing documents, and most investors learn that the hard way once. What did the gap between projected and actual look like on your last deal?","badResponse":"We build conservative, independent underwriting models so you never rely on broker pro formas.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"problem_questions","framework":"SPIN – Problem"},{"phase":"implication","question":"If you've deployed capital into an asset that's underperforming its pro forma — and that capital is now tied up instead of available for a better deal — what's the opportunity cost in terms of deals you've had to pass on?","goodResponse":"Opportunity cost of trapped capital is hard to measure but very real. The investors who underwrite conservatively and independently tend to compound their portfolio value significantly faster.","badResponse":"Underperforming assets trap capital. Better underwriting prevents that.","rapportOnGood":2,"rapportOnBad":-1,"skillTag":"implication_questions","framework":"SPIN – Implication"},{"phase":"need_payoff","question":"If you had an independent financial model on your next acquisition — one that stress-tests rent growth, cap rate compression, and exit timing — how much more confident would you feel putting a LOI on the table?","goodResponse":"That confidence is exactly what institutional investors buy with their underwriting teams. We give individual investors that same analytical firepower. Let me show you what a deal model review looks like.","badResponse":"We do independent underwriting. It's a flat fee per deal.","rapportOnGood":3,"rapportOnBad":0,"skillTag":"need_payoff","framework":"SPIN – Need-Payoff"}]]};
